nresume oj<erations Monday.\nTozier, Announcer\nFor WJR, Dies\nAttack of Appendicitis\nFatal to Radio Man\nf Obituaries\nAn acute attack of appendicitis\nwas fatal to Harold Lloyd Tozier,\n25, announcer for radio station\nW.IR, whose funeral will be at\n2 30 p m. Tuesday in William R.\nHamilton Chapel. 3975 Cass\nHe died fn Art Center Hospital\nFriday after an operation.\nMr. Tozier, who lived at fis6\nLothrop, bad been with WJR four\nyears. Formerly his home had\n\"been in Stevens Point. Wis.\nSurvivors nne the widow-.\nMichael Isabelk\u2019: a son. iVxter\nDean; a stepson, John Robert Mc-\nCracken Jr., and the parent'-. Mr\nand Mrs. Warren Tozier of Stev\nens Point.\nBurial will he in Wood lawn\ncemetery. Later tbe body will be\nremoved to Stevens Point\nServices will he conducted hy\nthe Rev C B. Allen Metropoli\ntan MrthodM Church.\nFuneral arrangement t were\nreported to the fimw tor:\nJOSEPH H. CROrTKXr. 63.\nAug 3. of a heart anatk in his\nhome at 7529 Lo/ier, Van Dyke\nMi Croteau was for many years\nbuilding superintendent ot the 11\nJ 3 Culbertson Co Survivor* uif*\nC'larr daughters. Mrs Florence\nGrafton. Mrs Arms Behom tnd\nSister Jeanne Marie; sons. Emil,\nHenry, Eugene. Dominique\nrnand, Reginald and Leo Serv\nices in state at the Sp.i rhek\nFuneral Chapel. 25531 Van Dyke\nnvenue. Center Line and funeral\nTuesday, 9 a m. at St. Clement'*\nChur'h. Van Dyke and Church\nroad*.\n.11 IIA DID \\s. 53 Aug 3. of a\nbean attack after long illnc**\nSurvivor* husband, Julius, sons,\nJohn. Albert, Karl. Rudolph and\npfc. Anthony, daughter, Th\u00bb r- i,\nmother. Mrs. Theresa N'eukam.\nbrother*. John artd Joseph \\eu\nkam Services; Monday. 9 a in.\npr re*idepre lbo|6 Eastwood avo\nrue. and 9 30 at St Jude Church,\n15711 E Seven Mile road. Burial\nMr Oliv# t Cemetery.\nNOTICE!\nAll Lyon, Inc. Employees\nreport for work on their\nregular shifts on\nMONDAY, AUGUST 6th\nLYON Inc\n13881 West Chicago Bjvd.\n-Aug. 5. 1R45\njjj v\nt'. S N\u00ab\\y photo, dtatnbutrd hv Intern*! n\u00bbt S' urd Thotoe\nA Jap carrier aflame at the Kure, Honshu, Jap I \u2022\u2022lie\nisland naval base after direct hits by Third Fleet earlier\nplanes. Water mushrooms up (right) from near misse*.\nThe ship was carefully camouflaged\u2014hut not well enough.\nBrown Picking 1\nPrison Probers\nLANSING, Aug 4 (UP)\u2014Selec- 1\ntion of a special legislative com\nmittee to investigate the state's\npenal 'cystcm will not he com\npleted until sometime next week,\nit was announced today by Lt.\nGov. Vernon J. Brown.\nThe lieutenant governor, a* pre\nsiding officer of ihe Senate, is\ndrawing up the committee as re\nquested in a resolution passed by\nDie Senate during the 1945 regu\nlar session.\nSeveral *rnatnrs already have\nbeen asked to serve on tlie com\nmit tee out have refused because\nof the pressure of personal husi\nnss. This was true \u2018of Senator\nHairy F. Hittle <R> of Lansing,\nwhom Brown had asked to pre\nside as chairman of the com\nmuter.\nFormation of a legislative com\nmittee to investigate Ihe state's\npenal rystem was prompted by\nAlly. Gin. John R. Dethmers' cx\n[m>s\u00b0 of graft, vice and corruption'\nin Jack-on State Prison.\n3 in Dearborn Race\nFor Mayor\nHubbard, Thomson,\nGuy in Primary\nMayor Orville L Hubbard *ork-,\ning hi* third term a* Dearborn's!\nchief executive, will have two op\nponent* (or the mayoralty nomina\ntion in Tuesday nonpartisan pri\nmaries\nRalph Guy ind James *Thom*on\nare contesting Hubbard's office i\nIn the councilmanic race*, with\n11 to be nominated, all present\nmembers of the sevrn-man council\nare seeking renomination. They\nan Council President Norman Ed\nwards. Ray S. Parker. Dr. Edward\nF. Fisher. Patrick Doyle. Joseph\nSchaefer. Howard Ternes and An\nthony I 'p< r. Contesting for their\n-eit.s are one woman and 13 men. 1\nMarguerite C. Johnson, Homer\nC P-t idle, Richard Gallo. Arthur\nG. Baker Severance W. Paget,\nRetry LlewClyn, M. f) Niekon,\nHarry A. Hoxie, Joseph M Ford.\nClarence M. Lewis, Charles J\nBradley, Walter Dorosh. Carl\nUglesber and Sam R, Maeeri.\nThere ate no content* for Dear\nborn\u2019* two municipal tudgships.\ncity rink or ritv treasurer a* flu\nincumbents have no opposition.\nt oll* will open at 7 a rn Central 1\nWar Time is a. m Detroit timr\u00bb\n*nd closr ;,t x p iti. Central War\nTin e (9 p. m. Detroit timei.\nA CAMOUFLAGED JAP CARRIER BLASTED BY ADM. HALSEY'S PLANES\nCandidates for Mayor Tell How\nThey Will Solve City\u2019s Problems\nFaced with problems arising from reconversion, housing, slum clear-!\nance, transportation and the many other duties of good government, De- 1\ntroit voters have an important decision to make in this 1945 election. First\nstep toward a happy and prosperous city in the postwar world, from the\nstandpoint of government, will be taken Tuesday at the municipal primary\nelection. Here are the platforms of the three leading candidates for mayor:\nMAYOR JEFFRIKS\nMayor Jeffrie*' campaign for\na louith term emphasizes his rec\nord a* mayor and a* a foimer\ncouncilman. Contending he has\nbrought to Detroit a ju*t and eco\nnomical government, conquering\nthe many problems which have\narisen from the war, the mayor\nhas argued that he 1* entitled\nto remain in office\n\"Only h fool claims to hr In\ndispensable,\" he said. \"But I\nsincerely believe my re-election\nas max or is justified by my\nrecord during the last six >cars.\nINHERITED DEFICIT\n\"When I became mayor In\n1010 I inherited an operating\ndeficit of $11.000,000. The credit\nstanding of Detroit xxas the\nworst ot any large city in the\ncountry. Our taxpayers xxere\nassessed inexcusably high inter\nest rates.\n\u201cSince 1940 xxe haxe operated\nxxithin the irieome and have ac\ncumulated Xi3,000.0(H) to he\nused in financing Detroit's post\nxxar improvements. And xxe\nhaxe paid oft almost $90,000,000\no| outsat riding indebtedness.\nINTEREST RATE I T\n\"By arguing xxith hankers,\nw e haxe decreased interest\nrates on Detroit bonds suffi\nciently to saxe the taxpayers\n$\",000,000 a year.\u201d\nOn the subject of \u00bbhr DSR.\nJeffries contended that his ad\nministration ha> accomplished a\ntransjiortation miracle, consider\ning the manpower shortage and\nthe city's inability to buy new\nequipment.\nHo said the daily load hn* in\ncreased from 1 100,000 to 2.000,-\n000, and that thi* unanticipated\nincrease of almost SO per cent\nhas been solved.\nH TI liE OF DSR\n\"During the xxar, xx hen\nneither manpower nor materials\nhaxe been axallahle for major\npublic Improvements, xxe have\nmade plans,\u201d he continued.\n\"We have the money mm to\ncarry out these plans. A \u00ab\u00bbu will\nsi ion see a new Detroit, com\nplete \\x itli a network of mod\nern expressways, modern trans\nportation and greatlv expanded\nr< i reational facilities.\n\\s mayor. I have had a pari\nIn making these plans. \\s\nmavor. I would like the privi\nlege of carrving them out.\nSOLVES VF.T PROBLEM\n\"Detroit Is prepared to meet\nthe problem* of the returning\nveterans. We have properly\nfinanced the Detroit Council of\nVeterans\u2019 Affairs. It provides\nhefp \u00abn\u00abt guidance to veterans\nwith a wide variety of service\nnot ottered by other agencies.\n\"'The years nhcad xsIII he cru\ncial years. The duties Htid obli\ngations imposed iqion the mayor\nof Detroit will present no fob\nfor ax amateur wholly inexper\nienced in goxernment.\n\"That\u2019s xxhy I xvant to br\nand I heliexe I ought to be\u2014\nre-elected.\"\nThe Detroit Times has far mote\nnationally famous features than\nany other Detroit newspaper,\nitiiiilM' ii iTi> T trr-rjir\n'j\u00a7 jpp iwi\ns HP m w\nMil jj\u00dfh\nSi v\nT 2 T Wt\n5 m&Mi 7l\n'ujKfcu; 9?'^'\njML. m\nj|^ wm\n'S\u2018vf J\niwammmammmm\nR. T. FRANKKNSTEEX 1\nRichard T. Frankensteen. vice\npresident ol the UAW-C'IO. has\npromised that it he is elected he\nwill use every municipal facility\nto bring about reconversion with\nout unemployment.\nHis \"program of action\" for the\ncity entails;\nI\u2014 Full co-operation hv the\nlocal government with Wash\nington to stabilize employment.\nEND BLACK MARKET\n\u2018i Elimination of the black\nmarket.\n3 Rapid transit through ex\ntensive improvements to the\nDSR.\n4\u2014A postwar airport at\nonce.\nft Slum clearance and im\nproved housing through both\npublic and private mean*.\nft New parks and reci\u00bbea\ntional lacilitie*\n7 -A campaign hv the city\nto tepeal the state sales tax.\nAFTER RATS AND WEEDS\nH Elimination of rats, rub\nbish and vvped*.\n9\u2014Appointment of a quali\nfied, non-political police rnm\nmissioner who \"will eliminate\nfavoritism and politic*.\nIO Adequate facility* for\nho-pitali/ation and rc-cmploy\nnient of veterans\nll New hospitals.\nIn answer to the charge* that\nhi* eleciion would mean control of\nthe city by union labor, Franken\nsteen said;\n\"I have stated again and\nagain that, when elerted mayor.\nI wilt he mayor for all of\nthe people. Mv only question\non any public problem will hr:\n\u2018Will it heneht the entire city?'\nSI AND ON AIRI'ORT\nPromising construction of a\nmodern airport, the I\u2019AW vice\npresident lias accused Mayor Jef\nfries n r \"wasting\" $300,000 on the\n\"itnpossible Dequindre *de.\u201d\n\u201cThe supreme court warned\nthat the Dequindre site might\nhe prevented hy injiinetion,\"\nFrankensteen sard, \"let the\nmavor stubbornly Insisted \u00ab\u00bbn\ncondemnation proceedings.\n\"The airport fiasco Illustrates\nagain the irresponsibility of the\nmayor; his Incompetence in\nhandling public affairs, and his\nwild spending of the taxpayers\u2019\nmoney.\n\"He ignores the experts\u2019 re\nport, which cost $.*,8,000. He\nignores the supreme collet- He\nignores the State Aviation Au\nthority.\n\"Investigattnn might Indicate\nthat the Wavne C minty Airport\nmay Ih* the smartest choice we\ncould make now. It is already\nthere, in an established airport 1\nrone, so there could be no resi\ndential opposition.\n\"It must not he forgotten that I\nwe already \u2018have $.,.000,000 in- j\nVested there.\n\"W hen I am elected mavor. In\ndealing with the vital airport\nproblem, I will follow the same\ncourse I plan for every public\nproblem. The question will not\nhe whether it benefits labor or\nanv group, hut whether It bene- j\nfits all of Detroit.\u201d\nJAMES I). FRIEL\nCoun:y Auditor Jamrs P. Friel\nhas :tressed in his cam|>a!gn for\nmayor a promise to protect the\nwelfare of returning veterans. At\nthr same time, however, he hav\nemphasized that his program will\nmean johs sot all workers in event\nof n postwar depression.\nHis platform includes;\n1 A trained staff of war\nveterans to handle veterans* af\nfairs and to guarantee that no\nman or woman who has served\nthe nation will bo forgotten in\nthe yean to come.\n2 Immediate improvement\nof the city\u2019s streets and alleys\nand extension of its sewers.\n3 Slum clearance without\ndelay.\n4 Improvement of PSR\nservice by immediate purchase\nof new buses and street cars\nr> Guaranteed weekly gar\nbage collection.\n\u2666i Replacement of the city\u2019s\ndilapidated school* purchase of\nnew school buses and a guaran\ntee of \"adequate pay\" lor\nteachers.\n7 -Expansion of medical fa\ncilities at Receiving Hospital\nand its branches.\nH -More parks, swimming\npools and beaches.\nft Municipal intervention to\nsustain harmony between man\nagement and labor.\n10 Adequate housing\nthrough the usp of public funds\nj if private capital fails to solve\nthis important problem.\n11 -Reorganization of most\nmunicipal departments to es\ntablish harmony, efficiency and\neconomy.\nFricl has planned an improve\nment program which will cost\n$150,000,000.\n\u201cConstruction of new schools,\nnew pavement and new sewers\nar*\u00bb the first johs to he done and\nthey are the first Johs for re\nturning veterans and laid-ofT\nwar workers, the candidate said.\nSI,I\u2019M PROBLEM\n\u201cX \u00bbna|or problem that must\nhe faced is created by our slums.\nThe are the symbols of in\nequality and are the breeding\nplaces of despondency Hnd de\nlinquency.\"\n\u201cThey must be cleaned up.'*\nFriel has pointed to his record\nas chairman of the county board\n,of auditors. Among accomplish\nmen Is he said, are the new sys\ntrm of purchasing, si ream-lining\nof the abstract department, and\na 50 per cent reduction on the\ncounty's insurance rose-.\n11l MA.V GOVERNMENT\n\u201cIf there is one word to char\nacterize the kind of government\nI would tight for if I were\nmayor, that word is \u2018human\u2019,\"\nFriel said.\n\"I am human enough to want\nto see ns keep our promises to\nour veterans, and to prevent\nsuffering and want among our\npeople\n\u201cl,rt iis look at Detroit as a\ncity of human brings\u2014of peo\nple; and we will plan properly\nfor them and go forward again\n1 Inward prosperity and peace.\"\n\n[lection Arouses\nLittle Interest\n(Continued from Page One)\nbut he raised this figure Saturday\nto 90,000.\nCity Clerk Thomas C. Lead\nbetter said the total w ill be bi\ntween 100,000 and 120.000.\nI\u2019nlike the hitter contents when\nlabor candidate* hid for the\nmayoralty in other year*, thr\npresence of Frankensteen in the\nyear's jace has not aroused the\nvoters.\nFRIEL FOR VETS\nCounty Auditor Friel ha* hasec\nhis campaign on a promise to pro\ntect the welfare of returning vet\nerans, while at the same tim<\nmodernizing Detroit with new\nparks, pavements, hospitals, rapic\n{transit and airport facilities.\nMayor Jeffries\u2019 bid for a fourtl\nterm is founded on his contentioi\nthat his record justifies continu\nance in office.\n8 COI NCILMEN RUN\nOf the nine couneilmen. eight\nare seeking re-eleetion. Council\nman Henry S. Sweeny is retiring\nThere are 22 other aspirants.\nCity Clerk Leadhetter and Citv\nTreasurer Coho will lie far in th<\nlead of their respective opjionenis\nTraffic Judge John I> Watts\nappointed to ihe bench by Gov\nKelly, is seeking election to tha 1\nj*o*t. Opposing him for the nomi\nnation are five candidate*.\nNever before ha* a pnman\nbeen held so early. It w as orderec\nin August this year so that ballot\nfor the November election can hi\n*ent to Detroiters in the far Pa\ncific and on other fronts.\n\u201cKI MBLES\" IIARCED\nIn an address Saturday night\nAuditor Friel charged that Mayoi\nJeffries ha* \u201cfumbled'\u2019 plans foi\npostwar improvements.\n\u201cThe mayor\u2019s own figures\nshow that he has only $I(W)\nworth of postwar work ready for\neach of our 200,000 veterans\u2014\nwith nothing left for workers on\nthe home front,\" Friel said.\n\u201cHe Isn\u2019t ready with a plan to\nprovide Johs for veterans and\nwar workers. He Isn\u2019t ready\nwith plans to rid Detroit of Its\nrun-dovvn-at-the-heel look. He\ndoesn\u2019t see our postwar pro\ngram. as I do. as vital planning\nfor johs for people.\"\nMayor Jrffrie-s. m several cam\npaign speeches, contended that h(\nhas a postwar program undei\nway\n\u201cDetroit successfully with\nstood the impact of war,\" the\nmayor told voters. \u201cOur munici\npal government is fully prepared\nfor the impact of |ieace.\nADVERT\u2019PIEMEN T\nATHLETE\u2019S FOOT\nIL Amsaing Wood or Solvm\nAN 14 Dart FREE TRIAL\nPp\u00df yi, R>P\u00abrWtalmttt\nBj I>> tinv matrrv bli\u00ab*-M\n|-,rm h- f\nK\nr\ncrotch of i lif\nI SEND NO MONEY. NO COST\nM UNLESS 100% SATISFIED!\n1 S mirf So\u00bb*\u00bb r\u00abIISi\u00abf Im Itrr\nM M *n.| (\u00abr 14 <l*V\u00bb\nM rr. \u2022\u2022'HI n\u00bb\u00bbl {*rnv un\n1 tullv DU <V-' E U><iw\n1 MAH COUPON TODAY mmmm\nU I WILEY PRODUCTS\nV f II S J\nM ylui\" v-\nf W ntvffHn! F\u00abr>\u00bb S\u00abt' t 111-\u2022\u00bb l* J\nW F.AOfT 14 -i\u00bbv\u00ab I fn'irfty\n\u25a0PRa rr*. 111 pSY\nHem -in-isl m y-' k\n\u25a0LNBfc*g\u00ab|iUU\u00ablllvO UK UW I tr J\nSsamf\nvnnrrss J\n*TATf __j\n8 World Fair j\nSites Offered\nDetroit Booster Body\nHolds First Session\nEight sites for a Detroit\nWorld's Farr, when war ends,\nhave been proposed to the Detroit\nWorld's hair Fact Finding Com\nmittee. which had its first meet\ning Saturday.\nFederal Judge Frank A. Picard,\nwho presided over the session, ex\nplained that the purpose <>t tht\norganization wav no! In promote\na fair, \u201chut to determine whether\nor not it is even possible to hold\none here.\u201d\nAs general chairman of the\ncommittee, he has api>ointed a\nsubcommittee on sites, which in\ncludes Alvin E. Harley, Eddie\nStinson. B. H. Acklcs. William C.\nCowling, Clair W. Ditchy, Ben\nDixon, George Emery. Henry T.\nEwald. Harry Fletcher, S. C. Had\nley, Richard Harfst, William fid\nward Kapp, Edward Laird. Amcdo\nLeone, Dan F. Lynch, Frank X.\nMartel, WiUiam M Packer, Fred\nW. Pearce, Elmer C Ray. William\nB. Stout, Nate S. Shapero. Ward\nVan Deusen, former Gov. Murray\nI). Van Wagoner. George Walker.\nJoseph Wolff and William J\ni Young.\n9,000 Quit Work\nAt Wright Plant\ni\nReduces B-29 Engine\nOutput 40 Per Cent\n1 CINCINNATI. Aug 1 f INS\nApproximately one-tlmd oi the\n27.000 employes of the Wright\nAeronautical Corp. plant in sub\nurban Lockland were on strike\ntonight, cutting down production\n'of B-29 engines by neatly 1U pci\ncent.\nThe strike started late Friday\nin one of the huge plant's two\nfoundries in protest against the\ntransfer of 14 aluminum foundry\nworkers to job* in lower pay\nclassification.\nEventually the strike spread to\nanother foundry and aT 8 a. rr.\ntoday all foundry ojicrations were\nat a stand*till Later workers in\nthe machine shop and on the h\nsemhly line* walked out in sup\nport of the strike.\nWealthy Tax Evader,\nFacing Prison, Dies\nNEW YORK, Aug 4 dT 1\nSamuel Greenberg, 59. wealthy\nclothing manufacturer, died in\nKnickerbocker Hospital today one\nday alter hr was scheduled to\nbegin a year's jail sentence for\ni tax evasion\nj Police said death resulted from\nan overdose of sleeping tablets\nHi* wife and son, Cpl. Lawrence\nGreenberg, found him ill m bed\nI yesterday morning at his home.\nSix Cenls a Ton Boost\nFor Coal Producers\nWASHINGTON Aug 1 itT\u00bb-\nOPA said today it had